2026-05-21 01:54:51,654 [INFO] auto_slr: [Assistant] extract_and_record 输出: {"user_identity": "researcher in medical field", "user_preference": "Systematic Review (Systematic Review)", "research_direction": "Dementia with Lewy bodies (DLB) and Dopamine transporter imaging using SPECT", "filter_requirements": "Search methods: MEDLINE, Embase, BIOSIS Previews, PsycINFO, CINAHL, LILACS, Web of Science; Selection criteria: Test accuracy studies with delayed verification, diagnostic case-control studies, two-gate studies; Participants: Dementia in secondary care and those meeting clinical criteria for DLB; Index test: SPECT or PET imaging; Reference standard: Neuropathological diagnosis at autopsy; Data collection: Two review authors independently selected studies; Analysis: 2x2 table, sensitivities, specificities with 95% CI; Methodology: QUADAS-2 tool", "rejection_reasons": "", "other_info": "Systematic Review (Systematic Review)\nResearch Objectives:\n(A) To estimate the accuracy of DAT imaging for diagnosis of DLB in people with dementia in secondary care.\n(B) To estimate the accuracy of DAT imaging for diagnosis of DLB in people with dementia in secondary care who are already suspected of having DLB on the basis of prior clinical work-up.\nSearch methods: MEDLINE (1946-2013), Embase (1980-2013), BIOSIS Previews (1926-2013), PsycINFO (1806-2013), CINAHL (1982-2013), LILACS (2013), Web of Science and Conference Proceedings (1945-2013).\nSelection criteria: Test accuracy studies with delayed verification, diagnostic case-control studies, two-gate studies with alternative diagnosis controls.\nParticipants:\n(A) Participants with dementia in secondary care,\n(B) Participants in secondary care meeting consensus clinical criteria for possible or probable DLB (other than the DAT imaging criterion).\nIndex test: SPECT or PET imaging of brain dopamine transporters.\nReference standard: Neuropathological diagnosis at autopsy.\nData collection and analysis: Two review authors independently selected studies, extracted data into 2x2 table, calculated sensitivities, specificities with their 95% confidence intervals. Used QUADAS-2 tool plus additional items to assess methodological quality.\nMain results:\nOne study applicable to first objective (A): Sensitivity and specificity for diagnosis of DLB in participants meeting clinical criteria or NINCDS-ADRDA criteria; Semiquantitative vs visual analysis; High risk of bias in participant selection and index test domains. Sensitivity 1.00 (95% CI: 0.66-1.00), specificity 0.92 (95% CI: 0.64-1.00) for semiquantitative; Sensitivity 0.86 (95% CI: 0.42-1.00), specificity 0.83 (95% CI: 0.52-0.98) for visual analysis.\nSecond objective (B): Sensitivity and specificity in baseline clinical suspicion; Semiquantitative had sensitivity 1.00 (95% CI: 0.63-1.00), specificity 1.00 (95% CI: 0.59-1.00); Visual analysis had lower accuracy with sensitivity 0.83 (95% CI: 0.36-1.00) and specificity 0.71 (95% CI: 0.29-0.96).\nAuthors' conclusions:\nOnly one study used neuropathological reference standard to assess accuracy of DAT imaging for DLB diagnosis; Small study size leads to imprecise sensitivity and specificity estimates; Suggests DAT imaging is more accurate than clinical diagnosis.\nNo studies using neuropathological reference standard have addressed the scenario where DAT imaging is considered a diagnostic test in people with possible DLB or assessed accuracy in people with mild dementia. However, included data suggest normal 123I-FP-CIT SPECT may be an accurate means of excluding DLB in cases of moderately severe dementia and strong suspicion.\nSemiquantitative ratings appeared more accurate than visual ratings in all analyses."}
